SwiftUI.answer:
Both `@ObservedObject` and `@StateObject` are used to track and manage external state in SwiftUI, but they behave differently in terms of ownership and lifecycle management.

* Use `@StateObject` when a view creates and owns an observable object.
* Use `@ObservedObject` when passing an already existing observable object to a subview.
* If a view is recreated frequently, `@ObservedObject` might cause data loss — use `@StateObject` instead.
* Combine them for efficient data sharing between parent and child views.

| Feature | `@ObservedObject` | `@StateObject` |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Ownership** | **Parent view** owns and provides the object | The **view itself** owns the object |
| **When to Use** | Pass an existing object to a subview | Create a new object **inside the view** |
| **State Persistence** | **Loses state** when the view is re-created | **Persists state** even if the view re-renders |
| **Re-initialization** | Object may **get recreated** when the view refreshes | Object is **created only once** and stays alive |
| **Best Use Case** | Passing shared models to child views | Storing view-specific state objects |

**@ObservedObject (Parent-Owned State) — Problem: Losing Data on Re-render**

```swift
class CounterModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var count = 0
}

struct ParentView: View {
    @State private var counter = CounterModel() // Parent owns it

    var body: some View {
        ChildView(counter: counter) // Passing down
    }
}

struct ChildView: View {
    @ObservedObject var counter: CounterModel

    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Count: \(counter.count)")
            Button("Increment") { counter.count += 1 }
        }
    }
}

```

📌 **How It Works:**

* `ParentView` owns the `CounterModel` and passes it to `ChildView`.
* `ChildView` **does not own** the model; it just observes changes.

📌 **What Happens on Re-render?**

* If `ParentView` **recreates** `CounterModel`, `ChildView` will get a **new instance**, losing previous data.

**@StateObject (View-Owned State) — Retaining Data Across Re-renders**

```swift
struct StateObjectExample: View {
    @StateObject private var counter = CounterModel() // View owns the state

    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Count: \(counter.count)")
            Button("Increment") { counter.count += 1 }
        }
    }
}

```

📌 **How It Works:**

* `StateObjectExample` **creates** and **owns** `CounterModel`.
* Even if the view **re-renders**, `counter` **remains unchanged**.

📌 **Why is This Better?**

* `@StateObject` **ensures the object is created only once**, so data is preserved across updates.

**When Should You Use @ObservedObject vs. @StateObject?**

| Use Case | Best Choice |
| --- | --- |
| Sharing an external data model | `@ObservedObject` |
| Keeping view-specific state alive | `@StateObject` |
| Parent owns the object and passes it to children | `@ObservedObject` |
| The object should not be recreated on every re-render | `@StateObject` |

**Using @StateObject and @ObservedObject Together**
In many real-world apps, you combine both `@StateObject` and `@ObservedObject`.

*Example: Parent Uses @StateObject, Child Uses @ObservedObject*

```swift
struct ParentView: View {
    @StateObject private var counter = CounterModel() // View owns the object

    var body: some View {
        ChildView(counter: counter) // Pass it down
    }
}

struct ChildView: View {
    @ObservedObject var counter: CounterModel // Observes updates

    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Count: \(counter.count)")
            Button("Increment") { counter.count += 1 }
        }
    }
}

```

📌 **Why Use Both?**

* The **parent owns the state** (`@StateObject`).
* The **child only observes the state** (`@ObservedObject`).
* This prevents `counter` from being reset when `ChildView` re-renders.

